Phase-1 lifecycle step: sets up per-run filesystem state and enforces billed-mode safety gates before the cage starts.

`prepare_run(r: &Resolved) -> Result<Prep, CageError>` is the entry point. For billed modes (per `mode_is_billed`), it first calls `ensure_clean_tree`, which shells out to `git status --porcelain` and errors if the tree is dirty (unless `r.allow_dirty`) or if `root` isn't a git repo at all. This gate exists because the cage mounts the workspace read-write and the only recovery path is `git` against the pre-run commit — a dirty starting tree breaks that guarantee. It then mints a fresh rundir (`mint_rundir`, named `ctxcage-<task_id>-<pid>` under `TMPDIR`, removing any stale dir of the same name first), writes the embedded `CAGE_RULES_MD` to `cage-rules.md`, and writes an empty regular file (`empty-mask`) used to mask secret paths via bind mount — `/dev/null` won't work here since bind mounts carry `nodev`. For billed modes only, it also resolves the claude runtime via `resolve_claude_runtime`, which needs the rundir and target root to synthesize `claude.json` and locate credentials.

Returns a `Prep` struct bundling `rundir`, `rules_file`, `mask_file`, and `claude: Option<ClaudeRuntime>` (`Some` only for billed modes) — this struct is consumed later by `teardown_run` for cleanup, so any new resource added here should have a corresponding teardown step. Errors surface as `CageError::Protocol` for the billed-mode gates (dirty tree, non-repo, missing claude runtime/credential) and `CageError::Io` for filesystem failures.